**Code Explanation:**

The code prepares the dataset for the Super-Resolution Denoising Autoencoder (SR-DAE) by performing the following steps: 1. Data Loading & Noise Injection: It loads the stacked signal maps for SO bands (90, 150, 217 GHz) and Planck bands (353, 545, 857 GHz). It then injects noise by randomly sampling from the 3000 SO noise realizations and the 100 Planck MC noise realizations. To optimize memory and disk I/O, Planck noise files are accessed using mmap_mode='r', loading only the required patches. 2. Feature Engineering: It constructs spectral difference maps (150-90 GHz and 217-150 GHz) to highlight the tSZ spectral signature. These difference maps are normalized by their respective global noise standard deviations to ensure consistent dynamic ranges. 3. Robust Scaling: The CIB auxiliary channels (353, 545, 857 GHz) are normalized using robust scaling (subtracting the global median and dividing by the global Interquartile Range) to prevent high-intensity foregrounds from dominating the input tensor. 4. Target Normalization & Masking: The ground truth tSZ maps are standardized to unit variance (zero mean, unit standard deviation). A binary significance mask is generated to identify physically significant baryonic structures where the original tSZ Compton-y parameter exceeds 10^-7. 5. Data Augmentation Pipeline: A PyTorch Dataset class (TSZDataset) is defined to handle the consolidated tensors. It implements on-the-fly data augmentation, including random horizontal/vertical flips and 90-degree rotations, ensuring rotational invariance during training. 6. Consolidation & Saving: The processed features are stacked into a single input tensor X of shape (1523, 5, 256, 256), alongside the target tensor Y and mask tensor M. These are saved as .npy files in the data/ directory, ready to be loaded by the DataLoader in the next step.

